{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11468"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11468","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11468"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.28,0.24,0.3,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4100"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40448"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4100"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11468"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25256"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"337"},{"type":"tags","id":"1111"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6487"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40448"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year old man with terminal pancreatic cancer is currently undergoing end of life care and is being managed on the palliative care ward. This afternoon he is seen to be increasingly restless, agitated and combative towards staff. This is out of character for the patient and he is also refusing food and water. The nurse who was with him this morning noted that he seemed rather confused and difficult to redirect, very different to how he was on the AM shift yesterday.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECentral in his medical history is the diagnosis of metastatic pancreatic carcinoma six months. He also has hypertension and Parkinson\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the patient is obviously agitated and his vital signs are only measured with difficulty. Despite reassurances from the nursing staff, he remains agitated. Some form of pharmacological intervention is considered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first line intervention?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Diazepam oral PRN","Midazolam subcutaneous PRN","Haloperidol subcutaneous PRN","Quetiapine oral PRN","Oxazepam oral PRN"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPharmacological management for agitation in palliative care patients is aimed at reducing the distress of the patient. These pharmacological interventions should be tailored to the specific patient and implemented when distress or agitation is significant and impacting patient care. It is fair to assume that the agitation exhibited by this patient may be in the context of delirium and as always non-pharmacological measures should be implemented first. Whilst this patient\u0027s agitation remains unchecked despite calming words and actions from the nursing staff, and extends to refusal to take anything by mouth, gentle persuasion to take a tablet should always be the first step. Should this not succeed, some form of parenteral therapy can be considered - so long as the staff understand that approach such a patient with a needle may worsen the agitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaloperidol \u003C/strong\u003Eis an appropriate first-line intervention for agitation. However, as the patient above has pre-existing Parkinson\u0027s disease, the risk of associated extrapyramidal side effects is significant and thus it is inappropriate in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuetiapine \u003C/strong\u003Eis type of second-generation/atypical antipsychotic and may be used when first generation antipsychotics are inappropriate due to their dopaminergic inhibition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShort-term \u003Cstrong\u003Ebenzodiazepines \u003C/strong\u003Emay be considered as adjuncts to the antipsychotics in situations where agitation requires additional treatment. Benzodiazepines are rarely indicated as sole treatment and may worsen agitation associated with delirium. Obviously if the patient\u0027s distressed state and agitation does not allow an oral medication to be administered, another route and drug may have to be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExceptions to the statement above are made for last days of life care and require expert input.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["First generation antipsychotics are inappropriate for individuals suffering from Parkinson\u0027s Disease"],"references":["https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.ap1.proxy.openathens.net/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Palliative%20Care\u0026topicfile=palliative-care-psychological-symptoms\u0026guidelinename=Palliative%20Care\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e518#toc_d1e518"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25256"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11468"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25256","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25256"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-20T15:08:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-11-20T15:08:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4100"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40448"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/337"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"End of life care","synonyms":["Palliative care","EOLC"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-10T15:37:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"1111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1111"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Aggression","synonyms":["Agitation","Difficulty controlling temper","Aggressiveness","Anger"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-07-23T10:25:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-1